Abstract:  A  FeIII-catalyzed  cycloaromatization reaction of  acyclic  diaryldiyn-3-ones  has  been  established.  The  reaction  proceeds  under  gentle  catalytic  conditions  with  good functional group tolerance, to offer a straightforward  and  5-brominated  benzo[b]fluorenones.  An  allenoate-type  nine-membered  organoferric  cyclic  species    and  an  alternative  concerted  mechanism were proposed in this reaction.  Keywords: Fe-catalysis • Cycloaromatization • Fluostatin  • Chemoselectivity • Benzo[b]fluorenone

(fluostatins  B−E,  and  difluostatin A) possess various bioactivities including  dipeptidyl  peptidases  III  inhibition,  antibacterial  and  antitumor  abilities.[1]  The  core  structure  of  the  families  tetracyclic  a  benzo[b]fluorenone  framework  (Figure  1).  Similar  rigid  polycyclic  hydrocarbon  scaffolds  have  been  widely  found  in  Kinamycin  antibiotics.[2]    In  the  1970s,  Omura  isolated  the  natural  occurring  diazo  compound  5-diazobenzo[b]fluorene  was  known  as  streptomyces  proteinase.[3]  Kinamycin  D  Kinobscurinone, ketoanhydrokinamycin and stealthin  C  are  representative  of  benzo[b]fluorene  natural  products  structurally  related  the  kinamycins.  Interestingly,  the  similar  structural  relationship  of  fluostatins  with  kinamycins  had  been  studied  and  a  mechanism  for  the  conversion  of  kinamycins  into  fluostatin  derivatives  has  been  suggested.[4]  Further  study  has  shown  benzofluorene  derivatives  to  have  applications  in  electroluminescent  and  photochromic  devices,  such  as  blue  light-emitting  OLEDs  and  organic lasers,[5] or as useful synthetic precursors for  the  preparation  of  bowl-shaped  polycyclic  aromatic  synthesis.[6]  Thus,  organic  hydrocarbons  developing  construct  advanced  methods  benzo[b]fluorene core structures holding potential for  providing versatile functionalities is a valuable task. Other than the longstanding biosynthesis strategy  of  the  benzofluorene  families,[2,7]  earlier  thermal  cycloisomerization of benzodiynes and triynes always  suffered  from limited functional  group tolerance and  poor  chemical  selectivity,[8]  due  to  the  fact  that  benzo[a]fluorenes  benzo[c]fluorenone  and  constitutional  isomers  could  be  frequently  observed  as a result of radical rearrangement and relief of steric  strain  in  the  thermal  conditions  (Scheme  1,  eq  1).[9]  Recently,  Jiang  reported  visible-light  induced or  base-controlled  bicyclization  reactions  resulted  in  various  benzofluorenones  or  benzofluorenols.[10]  Liu  synthesis  of  and  benzo[b]fluorenone  a  through  copper/Selectfluor-catalyzed  tandem  annulation  of  1,6-enynes.[11]  Our  group  has  been  interested  in  the  transition-metal-catalyzed  cycloisomerization  of  1,n- diynols  to  chemo-  and  regioselectively  prepare  divergent  carbo/heterocyclic  molecules.[12]  Recently,  we  developed  a  simple  approach  regarding  coinage- electrophilic  metal  cycloisomerizations  of  1,6-diynols  with  NXSs  (X  =  Br  or  I),  to  selectively  afford  halo-substituted  benzo[a]fluorenols, naphthalenes or quinolines under

very mild conditions.[13] Based on the prior work, we  tetracyclic  have  benzo[b]fluorenone  frameworks  can  be  efficiently  formed  from  1,n-enynols  or  diynols  via  oxidant- promoted  Meyer-Schuster  rearrangement/Schmittel  cyclization  sequences  (Scheme  1,  eq  3).[14]  In  this  reaction,  a  radical  mechanism  was  rationalized,  which should produce ene-allenol or yne-alleol as key  intermediates in the cycloisomerizaitons to induce the  following Schmittel-type oxidative cyclizations.   the  aforementioned  methods  are  practical  synthesis  of  benzofluorene  the  derivatives,  alkyl  or  aryl  functional  groups  have  always  been  compulsorily  introduced  at  the  5- position  of  the  resulting  tetracyclic  frameworks.  We  envisioned  that  if  a  synthetically  versatile  halogen  atom  could  be  directly  installed  at  this  position,  complex  benzo[b]fluorenones  with  structurally  divergent functional groups could be easily produced  by utilizing  the halogen groups as synthetic handles.  Inspired  by  our  previous  work  in  this  area,[13-14]  we  proposed that by employing diaryldiyn-3-ones 1 as a  suitable substrate and NBS as the halogen source, the  5-bromo-substituted  benzo[b]fluorenones  2  could  be  chemoselectively  catalytic  generated  conditions in a ont-pot protocol (Scheme 1, Eq. 4). We began the reaction condition studies by using 3- phenyl-1-(2-(p-tolylethynyl)phenyl)prop-2-yn-1-one  1a  and  N-bromosuccinimide  (NBS)  as  the  substrates  (Table 1). In the absence of any Lewis acid catalyst,  it was observed that the desired tetracyclic compound  in  5-bromobenzo[b]fluorenone  2a  was  anhydrous  Et2O  at  80  oC  with  a  19%  yield.  Poor  conversion  of  the  starting  material  1a  was  observed  and,  simultaneously,  a  small  amount  of  competitive  byproduct  2a'  was  isolated  under  the  conditions  (entry  1).[8c,15]  Slow  transformation  and  only  trace  amount of the desired product 2a was observed when  a  Brønsted  acid,  TfOH  or  TsOH  (10  mol%),  was  selected  as  a  catalyst  (entry  2).  Further  screening  of  the  reaction  conditions  did  not  offer  many  positive  results. We anticipated a new catalytic model should  be set up in this cycloaromatization chemistry.

Inspired by the fascinating role of transition-metals  in  the  synthesis  of  carbo/heterocyclic  molecules,  we  hypothesized  ortho- reactivity  alkynyllphenyl  ynones  1  could  still  be  activated  in  proper  catalytic  conditions.  As  can  be  seen  from  Table 1, initial examinations of different Lewis acids,  such  as  In(OTf)3,  Zn(OTf)2  and  Sc(OTf)3,  did  not  offer  any  satisfactory  results  (entries  3-5),  whereas  improved  yields  of  the  desired  product  2a  were  observed  when  Cu(OTf)2,  La(OTf)3,  Ni(OTf)2,  Fe(OTf)2  and  Fe(OTf)3  were  evaluated,  respectively  (entries  6-10).  Finally,  a  smooth  conversion  was  observed  when  Fe(OAc)2  was  utilized,  and  the  desired product 2a could be isolated in 62% yield in a  shorter reaction time (entry 11). To search for a more  environmentally  benign  catalytic  condition,  various  iron  salts  were  next  screened,  and  this  led  to  the  discovery  of  FeII-catalysts  such  as  FeSO4  and  .7H2O. While  this  chemistry  offered  one  bromo  atom  directly  at  the  5-position  of  the  benzo[b]fluorenone  core  structure,  other  synthetically  useful  halogen  substitutions, including fluorine (2h), chlorine (2c, 2i),  and  bromine  (2j),  can  also  be  incorporated  at  the  R3  position  and  provide  good  to  excellent  yields.  In  addition,  the  group  R2  with  fluorine  (2o)  or  chlorine  (2p and 2q) and bromine (2r and 2s) substituents also  underwent  the  reaction  smoothly  to  deliver  the  corresponding  halogenated  products  to  excellent  yields.  These  results  indicated  that  further  decorations  of  the  benzo[b]fluorenone  derivatives  could  be  easily  achieved  through  transition-metal- catalyzed  cross-coupling  reactions  when  employing  the halide substituents as synthetic handles.

Recently, interest in utilizing benzothiophene-based  polycyclic  heteroarenes  in  organic  electronic  and  photonic devices has increased, due to the integration  of  thiophene  into  a  rigid  π-conjugated  ring  systems,  which  could  enhance  π-electron  delocalization,  and  induce strong π-π stacking. Both of these results were  important  for  efficient  charge  transportation  in  the  fields  of  OLEDs  and   organic  field-effect  transistors  (OFETs).[17]  In  an  attempt  to  broaden  the  synthetic  utility  of  this  reaction,  2-thiophene  based  diynone  3  was  synthesized.  The  FeIII-catalyzed  cyclization  reaction  of  compound  3  with  NBS  in  ethyl  acetate  afforded the expected brominated tetracyclic product  4 with an 80% yield (Scheme 2, eq 3).   Scheme  2. In order to shed mechanistic insight of the reaction,  control experiments were conducted. For the reaction  of 1a under the catalysis of FeIII while in the absence  of  NBS,  the  product  2a'  could  be  isolated  in  78%  yield  in  anhydrous  ethyl  acetate  at  100  oC  for  5h  (Scheme  3).  A  previous  report  indicated  that  this  compound 2a' could be formed without the assistance  of  any  catalyst  in  72%  yield  in  anhydrous  toluene  when compound 1a was heated to 100 oC for 11h. [8c]   These results indicated that a homologue intermediate  species should be formed in the cyclization reaction,  which then react with two different electrophiles such  as Br+ or H+ to give the observed products 2a and 2a',  respectively.  Interestingly,  no  reaction  was  observed  in the reaction of compound 2a' with NBS under the  standard  FeIII-cataltzed  conditions  (Scheme  3).  This  result  the  direct  Friedel-Crafts  halogenation  mechanism  of  arenes  with  bromonium  species  (Br+)  should  be  excluded.  Moreover,  when  one equivalent of a typical radical scavenger,[ 18] such  as BHT, styrene or TEMPO,  was  added  individually  as  an  additive  under  the  standard  conditions,  the  corresponding  obviously  reactions  were  suppressed.  Therefore,  the  product  3a  could  be  isolated  within  a  20-79%  yields  yield,  which  indicates  that  the  radical-process  most  likely  should  be excluded in the transformation (Table 3). It should  be  noted  that  the  low  yield  reaction  from  TEMPO  (entry  3)  suggested  the  possible  oxidation  of  organometallic  species  with  this  oxidant  should  be  involved in the key step of the transformation.

In  conclusion,  we  have  successfully  developed  an  iron-catalyzed  cycloaromatization  reaction  of  to  efficiently  and  diaryldiynones  with  NBS  chemoselectively  5-bromo-substituted  benzo[b]fluorenones  with  excellent  functional  group tolerance with good to excellent yield. The  bromo  atom,  which  attached  at  the  fused  core  structure  of  the  products,  could  be  served  as  a  to  prepare  various  good  synthetic  handle  benzo[b]fluorenone derivatives, thus significantly  highlighting  the  synthetic  utility  of  this  reaction.  Studies  to  explore  the  synthetic  potential  for  the  construction  of  ben[b]fluorene  frameworks  are  underway  in  our  lab  and  the  results  will  be  reported in due course. at room temperature under N2 condition. The reaction  mixture  was  stirred  at  80  °C  for  about  2-4  h  (monitored  by  TLC).  The  reaction  was  cooled  down  to room temperature and diluted with brine (10.0 mL),  extracted  with  ethyl  acetate  (10.0  mL×3).  The  combined organic layers were dried over Na2SO4, and  concentrated  to  give  the  crude  product,  which  was  further  purified  by  column  chromatography  (eluent:  EA:PE=1:10)  the  desired  products  benzo[b]fluorenones 2.
